===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|coppe|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|*coppe}}, as in {{term|ātorcoppe||spider|lit=venom head|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|copp||top, summit, head|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*kuppaz||vault, round vessel, head}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*gū-||to bend, curve}}. Cognate with {{etyl|dum|-}} {{term|koppe|lang=dum}}, {{term|kobbe||spider|lang=dum}}. More at {{l|en|cobweb}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A [[spider]].

===Etymology 2===
Possibly from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|caper||to capture|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|capio|capere|lang=la|to seize, to grasp}}; or possibly from {{etyl|nl|en}} {{term|kapen||to steal|lang=nl}}, from {{etyl|fy|en}} {{term|kapia|kāpia|to take away|lang=fy}}, from {{etyl|ofs|en}} {{term|kapia|lang=ofs}}, to buy.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|copp}}

# {{context|transitive|formerly|_|dialect|now|_|informal|lang=en}} to [[obtain]], to purchase (as in drugs), to get hold of, to [[take]]
#* '''2005''', Martin Torgoff, ''Can't Find My Way Home'', Simon &amp; Schuster, page 10:
#*: Heroin appeared on the streets of our town for the first time, and Innie watched helplessly as his sixteen-year-old brother began taking the train to Harlem to '''cop''' smack.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to (be forced to) [[take]]; to [[receive]]; to [[shoulder]]; to [[bear]], especially [[blame]] or [[punishment]] for a particular instance of [[wrongdoing]].
#: When caught, he would often '''cop''' a vicious blow from his father
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to [[steal]]
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to [[adopt]]
#: ''No need to '''cop''' an attitude with me, junior.''
# {{context|intransitive|usually with "to"|slang|lang=en}} to [[admit]], especially to a crime.
#: ''I already '''copped''' to the murder. What else do you want from me?''
#: ''Harold '''copped''' to being known as "Dirty Harry".''
#* {{quote-book|title=Mr. Paradise|page=295|author=Elmore Leonard|year=2005|passage=He shot a guy in a bar on Martin Luther King Day and '''copped''' to first-degree manslaughter}}

